Outlier/ Anomaly Detection¶

In [16]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.pyplot import figure
import numpy as np

def plotOutliers(data, c):
    print("Feature Name:", c)
    figure(figsize=(18, 8), dpi=80)
    plt.plot([i for i in range(len(data[c].values))], data[c].values)
    df = np.array(data[c])
    print("Highest allowed",np.mean(df) + 3* np.std(df))
    print("Lowest allowed",np.mean(df) - 3* np.std(df))
    H = np.mean(df) + 3* np.std(df)
    L = np.mean(df) - 3* np.std(df)
    values = df[(df > H) | (df < L)]
    
    if len(values) < 50:
        print(values)
    R = []
    for i in data[c].values:
        if i > H or i < L:
            R.append(i)
        else:
            R.append(data[c].mean())      
    plt.plot([i for i in range(len(data[c].values))], R, linestyle='None', marker="*", markersize=15, label="Outliers")
    plt.title(c)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Plot Histogram¶

In [34]:
def showHist(data, columnName):
    fig, a =  plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 5))
    
    try:
        a[0].hist(data[data["gender"] == "Male"][columnName])
        a[1].hist(data[data["gender"] == "Female"][columnName])
    except:
        data[data["gender"] == "Male"][columnName].value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='barh', ax=a[0])
        data[data["gender"] == "Female"][columnName].value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='barh', ax=a[1])
    
    a[0].set_title(columnName + ' - Male')
    a[1].set_title(columnName + ' - Female')
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.125,
                            bottom=0.1, 
                            right=0.9, 
                            top=0.9, 
                            wspace=0.4, 
                            hspace=0.35)
    plt.show()

One Hot Encoding for Features¶

In [53]:
users1_country = pd.get_dummies(users1["country"], prefix="country_")
users1[users1_country.columns] = users1_country
users1 = users1.drop(columns="country")

users1_gender= pd.get_dummies(users1["gender"], prefix="gender_")
users1[users1_gender.columns] = users1_gender
users1 = users1.drop(columns="gender")

    kmeans.fit(scaled_yes)

Recommendation System¶

Recommendation system - this will recommend users on the basis of similarities. This will help system to recommend users to each other to increase users interaction witj each other, hence increase system usability.

In [141]:

In [143]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaled_feature = scaler.fit_transform(active_users)

model_knn_item = NearestNeighbors(metric = "cosine", algorithm = 'brute')
model_knn_item.fit(scaled_feature)
    
def findkSimilarArtists(item_id, ratings, k=5):
    
    """
    This is same as findkSimilarUsers in functionality
    """
    similarities=[]
    indices=[]

    # find loc of book
    loc = ratings.index.get_loc(item_id)
    
    columns = ratings.columns
    ratings = scaler.transform(ratings)
    ratings = pd.DataFrame(data=ratings, columns=columns)
    
    # calculate similarity
    distances, indices = model_knn_item.kneighbors(ratings.iloc[loc, :].values.reshape(1, -1), n_neighbors = k)
    similarities = 1-distances.flatten()
    return similarities,indices
